# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: aircraft-engine-controls
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] A significant part of **aeronautical science** is a branch of dynamics called aerodynamics, which deals with the motion of air and the way that it interacts with objects in motion, such as an aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Attempts to fly without any real aeronautical understanding have been made from the earliest times, typically by constructing wings and jumping from a tower with crippling or lethal results.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Wiser investigators sought to gain some rational understanding through the study of bird flight.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Medieval Islamic Golden Age scientists such as Abbas ibn Firnas also made such studies.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] The founders of modern aeronautics, Leonardo da Vinci in the Renaissance and Cayley in 1799, both began their investigations with studies of bird flight.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Man-carrying kites are believed to have been used extensively in ancient China.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] In 1282 the Italian explorer Marco Polo described the Chinese techniques then current.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] The Chinese also constructed small hot air balloons, or lanterns, and rotary-wing toys.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] An early European to provide any scientific discussion of flight was Roger Bacon, who described principles of operation for the lighter-than-air balloon and the flapping-wing ornithopter, which he envisaged would be constructed in the future.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] The lifting medium for his balloon would be an "aether" whose composition he did not know.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] In the late fifteenth century, Leonardo da Vinci followed up his study of birds with designs for some of the earliest flying machines, including the flapping-wing ornithopter and the rotating-wing helicopter.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Although his designs were rational, they were not based on particularly good science.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Many of his designs, such as a four-person screw-type helicopter, have severe flaws.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Da Vinci's work was lost after his death and did not reappear until it had been overtaken by the work of George Cayley.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] The modern era of lighter-than-air flight began early in the 17th century with Galileo's experiments in which he showed that air has weight.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Around 1650 Cyrano de Bergerac wrote some fantasy novels in which he described the principle of ascent using a substance (dew) he supposed to be lighter than air, and descending by releasing a controlled amount of the substance.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Francesco Lana de Terzi measured the pressure of air at sea level and in 1670 proposed the first scientifically credible lifting medium in the form of hollow metal spheres from which all the air had been pumped out.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] These would be lighter than the displaced air and able to lift an airship.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] His proposed methods of controlling height are still in use today; by carrying ballast which may be dropped overboard to gain height, and by venting the lifting containers to lose height.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] In practice de Terzi's spheres would have collapsed under air pressure, and further developments had to wait for more practicable lifting gases.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] From the mid-18th century the Montgolfier brothers in France began experimenting with balloons.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Their balloons were made of paper, and early experiments using steam as the lifting gas were short-lived due to its effect on the paper as it condensed.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Meanwhile, the discovery of hydrogen led Joseph Black in c.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] 1780 to propose its use as a lifting gas, though practical demonstration awaited a gas-tight balloon material.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] On hearing of the Montgolfier Brothers' invitation, the French Academy member Jacques Charles offered a similar demonstration of a hydrogen balloon.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Charles and two craftsmen, the Robert brothers, developed a gas-tight material of rubberised silk for the envelope.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] The hydrogen gas was to be generated by chemical reaction during the filling process.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] The Montgolfier designs had several shortcomings, not least the need for dry weather and a tendency for sparks from the fire to set light to the paper balloon.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] The manned design had a gallery around the base of the balloon rather than the hanging basket of the first, unmanned design, which brought the paper closer to the fire.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] On their free flight, De Rozier and d'Arlandes took buckets of water and sponges to douse these fires as they arose.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] On the other hand, the manned design of Charles was essentially modern.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] As a result of these exploits, the hot air balloon became known as the *Montgolfière* type and the gas balloon the *Charlière*.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Charles and the Robert brothers' next balloon, *La Caroline*, was a Charlière that followed Jean Baptiste Meusnier's proposals for an elongated dirigible balloon, and was notable for having an outer envelope with the gas contained in a second, inner ballonet.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] On 19 September 1784, it completed the first flight of over 100 kilometres (62 mi), between Paris and Beuvry, despite the man-powered propulsive devices proving useless.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] The balloon envelope was made of goldbeater's skin.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] The first flight ended in disaster and the approach has seldom been used since.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Sir George Cayley (1773–1857) is widely acknowledged as the founder of modern aeronautics.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] He was first called the "father of the aeroplane" in 1846 and Henson called him the "father of aerial navigation." He was the first true scientific aerial investigator to publish his work, which included for the first time the underlying principles and forces of flight.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] In 1809 he began the publication of a landmark three-part treatise titled "On Aerial Navigation" (1809–1810).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] He developed the modern conventional form of the fixed-wing aeroplane having a stabilising tail with both horizontal and vertical surfaces, flying gliders both unmanned and manned.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] He introduced the use of the whirling arm test rig to investigate the aerodynamics of flight, using it to discover the benefits of the curved or cambered aerofoil over the flat wing he had used for his first glider.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] He also identified and described the importance of dihedral, diagonal bracing and drag reduction, and contributed to the understanding and design of ornithopters and parachutes.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Another significant invention was the tension-spoked wheel, which he devised in order to create a light, strong wheel for aircraft undercarriage.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] During the 19th century, Cayley's ideas were further developed, tested, and formalised.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Public and scientific interest in aeronautics grew during the Victorian era, with notable contributions from figures such as John Stringfellow, James Glaisher, Francis Wenham, and Frederick Brearey.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Wenham, Glaisher, and Brearey co-founded the Aeronautical Society of Great Britain in 1866, together with the 8th Duke of Argyll.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Although aeronautical research at the time remained largely experimental, the Society played an important role in promoting heavier-than-air flight, including through the First Aeronautical Exhibition held in 1868 at The Crystal Palace.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] These developments, along with growing international interest, helped lay the groundwork for the later work of Horatio Phillips among others, but more importantly of Otto Lilienthal, a German engineer and businessman who became known as the "flying man".
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] He was the first person to make well-documented, repeated, successful flights with gliders, therefore making the idea of "heavier than air" a reality.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Newspapers and magazines published photographs of Lilienthal gliding, favourably influencing public and scientific opinion about the possibility of flying machines becoming practical.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] His work led to the development of the modern wing.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] His flight attempts in Berlin in the year 1891 are seen as the beginning of human flight and the "Lilienthal Normalsegelapparat" is considered to be the first air plane in series production, making the *Maschinenfabrik Otto Lilienthal* in Berlin the first air plane production company in the world.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Otto Lilienthal is often referred to as either the "father of aviation" or "father of flight".
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Aeronautics may be divided into three main branches, Aviation, Aeronautical science and Aeronautical engineering.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Aviation is the art or practice of aeronautics.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Historically aviation meant only heavier-than-air flight, but nowadays it includes flying in balloons and airships.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Aeronautical engineering covers the design and construction of aircraft, including how they are powered, how they are used and how they are controlled for safe operation.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] A major part of aeronautical engineering is aerodynamics, the science of passing through the air.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] With the increasing activity in space flight, nowadays aeronautics and astronautics are often combined as aerospace engineering.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] The science of aerodynamics deals with the motion of air and the way that it interacts with objects in motion, such as an aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] A rocket or rocket vehicle is a missile, spacecraft, aircraft or other vehicle which obtains thrust from a rocket engine.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] In all rockets, the exhaust is formed entirely from propellants carried within the rocket before use.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Rocket engines work by action and reaction.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Rocket engines push rockets forwards simply by throwing their exhaust backwards extremely fast.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Rockets for military and recreational uses date back to at least 13th-century China.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Significant scientific, interplanetary and industrial use did not occur until the 20th century, when rocketry was the enabling technology of the Space Age, including setting foot on the Moon.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Rockets are used for fireworks, weaponry, ejection seats, launch vehicles for artificial satellites, human spaceflight and exploration of other planets.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] While comparatively inefficient for low speed use, they are very lightweight and powerful, capable of generating large accelerations and of attaining extremely high speeds with reasonable efficiency.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Chemical rockets are the most common type of rocket and they typically create their exhaust by the combustion of rocket propellant.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] Chemical rockets store a large amount of energy in an easily released form, and can be very dangerous.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aeronautics] However, careful design, testing, construction and use minimizes risks.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Air-cooled engines are widely seen in applications where weight or simplicity is the primary goal.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Their simplicity makes them suited for uses in small applications like chainsaws and lawn mowers, as well as small generators and similar roles.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] These qualities also make them highly suitable for aviation use, where they are widely used in general aviation aircraft and as auxiliary power units on larger aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Their simplicity, in particular, also makes them common on motorcycles.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Most modern internal combustion engines are cooled by a closed circuit carrying liquid coolant through channels in the engine block and cylinder head.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] A fluid in these channels absorbs heat and then flows to a heat exchanger or radiator where the coolant releases heat into the air (or raw water, in the case of marine engines).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Thus, while they are not *ultimately* cooled by the liquid, as the heat is exchanged with some other fluid like air, because of the liquid-coolant circuit they are known as *liquid-cooled*.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] In contrast, heat generated by an air-cooled engine is released directly into the air.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Typically this is facilitated with metal fins covering the outside of the cylinder head and cylinders which increase the surface area that air can act on.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Air may be force fed with the use of a fan and shroud to achieve efficient cooling with high volumes of air or simply by natural air flow with well designed and angled fins.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] In all combustion engines, a great percentage of the heat generated, around 44%, escapes through the exhaust.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Another 8% or so ends up in the oil, which itself has to be cooled in an oil cooler.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] This means less than half of the heat has to be removed through other systems.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] In an air-cooled engine, only about 12% of the heat flows out through the metal fins.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Air cooled engines usually run noisier, however it provides more simplicity which gives benefits when it comes to servicing and part replacement and is usually cheaper to be maintained.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Many motorcycles use air cooling for the sake of reducing weight and complexity.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Few current production automobiles have air-cooled engines (such as Tatra 815), but historically it was common for many high-volume vehicles.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] The orientation of the engine cylinders is commonly found in either single-cylinder or coupled in groups of two, and cylinders are commonly oriented in a horizontal fashion as a flat engine, while vertical straight-four engine have been used.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] During the 1920s and 30s there was a great debate in the aviation industry about the merits of air-cooled vs. liquid-cooled designs.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] At the beginning of this period, the liquid used for cooling was water at ambient pressure.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] The amount of heat carried away by a fluid is a function of its capacity and the difference in input and output temperatures.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] As the boiling point of water is reduced with lower pressure, and the water could not be efficiently pumped as steam, radiators had to have enough cooling power to account for the loss in cooling power as the aircraft climbed.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] The resulting radiators were quite large and caused a significant amount of aerodynamic drag.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] This placed the two designs roughly equal in terms of power to drag, but the air-cooled designs were almost always lighter and simpler.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] In 1921, the US Navy, largely due to the efforts of Commander Bruce G.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Leighton, decided that the simplicity of the air-cooled design would result in less maintenance workload, which was paramount given the limited working area of aircraft carriers.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Leighton's efforts led to the Navy underwriting air-cooled engine development at Pratt & Whitney and Wright Aeronautical.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Most other groups, especially in Europe where aircraft performance was rapidly improving, were more concerned with the issue of drag.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] While air-cooled designs were common on light aircraft and trainers, as well as some transport aircraft and bombers, liquid-cooled designs remained much more common for fighters and high-performance bombers.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] The drag issue was upset by the 1929 introduction of the NACA cowl, which greatly reduced the drag of air-cooled engines in spite of their larger frontal area, and the drag related to cooling was at this point largely even.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] This also led to development work attempting to eliminate the radiator entirely using evaporative cooling, allowing it to turn to steam and running the steam through tubes located just under the skin of the wings and fuselage, where the fast moving outside air condensed it back to water.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] While this concept was used on a number of record-setting aircraft in the late 1930s, it always proved impractical for production aircraft for a wide variety of reasons.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] In 1929, Curtiss began experiments replacing water with ethylene glycol in a Curtiss D-12 engine.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Ethylene glycol could run up to 250°C and reduced the radiator size by 50% compared to water-cooled designs.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] The experiments were extremely successful and by 1932 the company had switched all future designs to this coolant.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] At the time, Union Carbide held a monopoly on the industrial process to make ethylene glycol, so it was initially used only in the US, with Allison Engines picking it up soon after.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] It was not until the mid-1930s that Rolls-Royce adopted it as supplies improved, converting all of their engines to ethylene glycol.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] With the much smaller radiators and less fluid in the system, the weight and drag of these designs was well below contemporary air-cooled designs.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] On a weight basis, these liquid-cooled designs offered as much as 30% better performance.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] In the late- and post-war era, the high-performance field quickly moved to jet engines.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] This took away the primary market for late-model liquid-cooled engines.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Those roles that remained with piston power were mostly slower designs and civilian aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] In these roles, the simplicity and reduction in servicing needs is far more important than drag, and from the end of the war on almost all piston aviation engines have been air-cooled, with few exceptions.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] As of 2020, most of the engines manufactured by Lycoming and Continental are used by major manufacturers of light aircraft Cirrus, Cessna and so on.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Other engine manufactures using air-cooled engine technology are ULPower and Jabiru, more active in the Light-Sport Aircraft (LSA) and ultralight aircraft market.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Rotax uses a combination of air-cooled cylinders and liquid-cooled cylinder heads.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Some small diesel engines, e.g. those made by Deutz AG and Lister Petter are air-cooled.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Probably the only big Euro 5 truck air-cooled engine (V8 320 kW power 2100 N·m torque one) is being produced by Tatra.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] BOMAG part of the FAYAT group also utilizes an air cooled inline 6 cylinder motor, in many of their construction vehicles.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Stationary or portable engines were commercially introduced early in the 1900s.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] The first commercial production was by the New Way Motor Company of Lansing, Michigan, US.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] The company produced air-cooled engines in single and twin cylinders in both horizontal and vertical cylinder format.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Subsequent to their initial production which was exported worldwide, other companies took up the advantages of this cooling method, especially in small portable engines.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-cooled] Applications include mowers, generators, outboard motors, pump sets, saw benches and auxiliary power plants and more.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] In an internal combustion engine or industrial furnace, the air–fuel ratio is an important measure for anti-pollution and performance-tuning reasons.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] If exactly enough air is provided to completely burn all of the fuel (**stoichiometric combustion**), the ratio is known as the **stoichiometric mixture**, often abbreviated to **stoich**.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] Ratios lower than stoichiometric (where the fuel is in excess) are considered "rich".
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] Rich mixtures are less efficient, but may produce more power and burn cooler.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] Ratios higher than stoichiometric (where the air is in excess) are considered "lean".
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] Lean mixtures are more efficient but may cause higher temperatures, which can lead to the formation of nitrogen oxides.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] Some engines are designed with features to allow lean-burn.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] For precise air–fuel ratio calculations, the oxygen content of combustion air should be specified because of different air density due to different altitude or intake air temperature, possible dilution by ambient water vapor, or enrichment by oxygen additions.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] An **air-fuel ratio meter** monitors the air–fuel ratio of an internal combustion engine.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] Also called **air–fuel ratio gauge**, **air–fuel meter**, or **air–fuel gauge**, it reads the voltage output of an oxygen sensor, sometimes also called **AFR sensor** or lambda sensor.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] The original narrow-band oxygen sensors became factory installed standard in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] In recent years a newer and much more accurate wide-band sensor, though more expensive, has become available.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] Most stand-alone narrow-band meters have 10 LEDs and some have more.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] Also common, narrow band meters in round housings with the standard mounting 52 and 67 mm (2+1⁄16 and 2+5⁄8 in) diameters, as other types of car 'gauges'.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] Analogue 'needle' style gauges are also available.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] In theory, a stoichiometric mixture has just enough air to completely burn the available fuel.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] In practice, this is never quite achieved, due primarily to the very short time available in an internal combustion engine for each combustion cycle.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] Most of the combustion process is completed in approximately 2 milliseconds at an engine speed of 6,000 revolutions per minute (100 revolutions per second, or 10 milliseconds per revolution of the crankshaft.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] For a four-stroke engine this would mean 5 milliseconds for each piston stroke, and 20 milliseconds to complete one 720 degree Otto cycle).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] This is the time that elapses from the spark plug firing until 90% of the fuel–air mix is combusted, typically some 80 degrees of crankshaft rotation later.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] Catalytic converters are designed to work best when the exhaust gases passing through them are the result of nearly perfect combustion.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] A perfectly stoichiometric mixture burns very hot and can damage engine components if the engine is placed under high load at this fuel–air mixture.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] Due to the high flame temperatures at this mixture, detonation is possible under high load.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] (Detonation is known as knocking or pinging).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] Such detonation can cause serious engine damage as the uncontrolled burning of the fuel-air mix can create very high pressures in the cylinder.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] As a consequence, stoichiometric mixtures are only used under light to low-moderate load conditions.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] For acceleration and high-load conditions, a richer mixture (lower air–fuel ratio) is used to produce cooler combustion products and so avoid overheating of the cylinder head, and thus prevent detonation.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] The stoichiometric mixture for a gasoline engine is the ideal ratio of air to fuel that burns all fuel with no excess air.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] For gasoline fuel, the stoichiometric air–fuel mixture is about 14.7:1 i.e. for every one gram of fuel, 14.7 grams of air are required.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] Any mixture greater than 14.7:1 is considered a lean mixture; any less than 14.7:1 is a rich mixture – given perfect (ideal) "test" fuel (gasoline consisting of solely *n*-heptane and iso-octane).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] In reality, most fuels consist of a combination of heptane, octane, a handful of other alkanes, plus additives including detergents, and possibly oxygenators such as MTBE (methyl *tert*-butyl ether) or ethanol/methanol.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] These compounds all alter the stoichiometric ratio, with most of the additives pushing the ratio downward (oxygenators bring extra oxygen to the combustion event in liquid form that is released at the time of combustions; for MTBE-laden fuel, a stoichiometric ratio can be as low as 14.1:1).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] Vehicles that use an oxygen sensor or other feedback loops to control fuel to air ratio (lambda control), compensate automatically for this change in the fuel's stoichiometric rate by measuring the exhaust gas composition and controlling fuel volume.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] Vehicles that use oxygen sensors can monitor the air–fuel ratio with an air–fuel ratio meter.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] In the typical air to natural gas combustion burner, a double-cross limit strategy is employed to ensure ratio control.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] The strategy involves adding the opposite flow feedback into the limiting control of the respective gas (air or fuel).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] This assures ratio control within an acceptable margin.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] There are other terms commonly used when discussing the mixture of air and fuel in internal combustion engines.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] Air-fuel ratio is the ratio between the *mass* of air and the mass of fuel in the air-fuel mix at any given moment.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] The mass is the mass of all constituents that compose the air or fuel, whether they take part in the combustion or not.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] For pure octane the stoichiometric mixture is approximately 15.1:1, or *λ* of 1.00 exactly.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] In naturally aspirated engines powered by octane, maximum power is frequently reached at AFRs ranging from 12.5 to 13.3:1 or *λ* of 0.850 to 0.901.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] The air-fuel ratio of 12:1 is considered as the maximum output ratio, whereas the air-fuel ratio of 16:1 is considered as the maximum fuel economy ratio.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] Air–fuel equivalence ratio, *λ* (lambda), is the ratio of actual AFR to stoichiometry for a given mixture.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] *λ* = 1.0 is at stoichiometry, rich mixtures *λ* < 1.0, and lean mixtures *λ* > 1.0.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] There is a direct relationship between *λ* and AFR.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] To calculate AFR from a given *λ*, multiply the measured *λ* by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] Alternatively, to recover *λ* from an AFR, divide AFR by the stoichiometric AFR for that fuel.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] Because the composition of common fuels varies seasonally, and because many modern vehicles can handle different fuels when tuning, it makes more sense to talk about *λ* values rather than AFR.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] Most practical AFR devices actually measure the amount of residual oxygen (for lean mixes) or unburnt hydrocarbons (for rich mixtures) in the exhaust gas.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] The **fuel–air equivalence ratio**, *Φ* (phi), of a system is defined as the ratio of the fuel-to-oxidizer ratio to the stoichiometric fuel-to-oxidizer ratio.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] where *m* represents the mass, *n* represents a number of moles, subscript st stands for stoichiometric conditions.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] The advantage of using equivalence ratio over fuel–oxidizer ratio is that it takes into account (and is therefore independent of) both mass and molar values for the fuel and the oxidizer.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] Consider, for example, a mixture of one mole of ethane (C 2H 6) and one mole of oxygen (O 2).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] To compare it with the equivalence ratio, we need to determine the fuel–oxidizer ratio of ethane and oxygen mixture.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] This is not the case if one uses fuel–oxidizer ratio, which takes different values for different mixtures.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] In industrial fired heaters, power plant steam generators, and large gas-fired turbines, the more common terms are percent excess combustion air and percent stoichiometric air.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] For example, excess combustion air of 15 percent means that 15 percent more than the required stoichiometric air (or 115 percent of stoichiometric air) is being used.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] A combustion control point can be defined by specifying the percent excess air (or oxygen) in the oxidant, or by specifying the percent oxygen in the combustion product.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/air-fuel-ratio] An air–fuel ratio meter may be used to measure the percent oxygen in the combustion gas, from which the percent excess oxygen can be calculated from stoichiometry and a mass balance for fuel combustion.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-engine-controls] *Right* - The left magneto p-lead is grounded, and the right is open.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-engine-controls] This disables the left magneto and enables the right magneto only.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-engine-controls] *Left* - The right magneto p-lead is grounded, and the left is open.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-engine-controls] This disables the right magneto and enables the left magneto only.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-engine-controls] *Both* - This is the normal operating configuration, both p-leads are open, enabling both magnetos.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-engine-controls] *Start* - The pinion gear on the starter motor is engaged with the flywheel and the starter motor runs to turn the engine over.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-engine-controls] In most cases, only the left magneto is active (the right p-lead is grounded) due to timing differences between the magnetos at low RPMs.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-engine-controls] In an aircraft with a **fixed-pitch propeller**, there is no direct control over the propeller rotational speed, which depends on the airspeed and loading.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-engine-controls] Therefore, the pilot has to pay attention to the RPM indicator and adjust the throttle/power lever in order to maintain the desired constant speed of the propeller.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-engine-controls] For example, when the airspeed reduces and the loading increases (e.g., in a climb), RPM will decrease and the pilot has to increase the throttle/power.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-engine-controls] When the airspeed increases and the loading decreases (e.g., in a dive), the RPM will increase and the pilot has to decrease the throttle/power in order to prevent RPM from exceeding the operational limits and damaging the motor.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-engine-controls] Restricting the volume of cooling airflow too much.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-engine-controls] Insufficient delivery of lubricating oil to the engine's moving parts.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] A conventional fixed-wing **aircraft flight control system** consists of flight control surfaces, the respective cockpit controls, connecting linkages, and the necessary operating mechanisms to control an aircraft's direction in flight.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Aircraft engine controls are also considered flight controls as they change speed.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] The fundamentals of aircraft controls are explained in flight dynamics.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] This article centers on the operating mechanisms of the flight controls.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] The basic system in use on aircraft first appeared in a readily recognizable form as early as April 1908, on Louis Blériot's Blériot VIII pioneer-era monoplane design.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] The control yokes also vary greatly among aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Centre sticks also vary between aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Some are directly connected to the control surfaces using cables, others (fly-by-wire airplanes) have a computer in between which then controls the electrical actuators.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Flight control has long been taught in such fashion for many decades, as popularized in ab initio instructional books such as the 1944 work Stick and Rudder.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] In some aircraft, the control surfaces are not manipulated with a linkage.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] In ultralight aircraft and motorized hang gliders, for example, there is no mechanism at all.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Instead, the pilot just grabs the lifting surface by hand (using a rigid frame that hangs from its underside) and moves it.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] In addition to the primary flight controls for roll, pitch, and yaw, there are often secondary controls available to give the pilot finer control over flight or to ease the workload.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Many aircraft have wing flaps, controlled by a switch or a mechanical lever or in some cases are fully automatic by computer control, which alter the shape of the wing for improved control at the slower speeds used for take-off and landing.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Other secondary flight control systems may include slats, spoilers, air brakes and variable-sweep wings.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Mechanical or manually operated flight control systems are the most basic method of controlling an aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] They were used in early aircraft and are currently used in small aircraft where the aerodynamic forces are not excessive.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] A manual flight control system uses a collection of mechanical parts such as pushrods, tension cables, pulleys, counterweights, and sometimes chains to transmit the forces applied to the cockpit controls directly to the control surfaces.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Turnbuckles are often used to adjust control cable tension.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] The Cessna Skyhawk is a typical example of an aircraft that uses this type of system.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Gust locks are often used on parked aircraft with mechanical systems to protect the control surfaces and linkages from damage from wind.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Some aircraft have gust locks fitted as part of the control system.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Increases in the control surface area, and the higher airspeeds required by faster aircraft resulted in higher aerodynamic loads on the flight control systems.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] As a result, the forces required to move them also become significantly larger.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Consequently, complicated mechanical gearing arrangements were developed to extract maximum mechanical advantage in order to reduce the forces required from the pilots.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] This arrangement can be found on bigger or higher performance propeller aircraft such as the Fokker 50.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Some mechanical flight control systems use servo tabs that provide aerodynamic assistance.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Servo tabs are small surfaces hinged to the control surfaces.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] The flight control mechanisms move these tabs, aerodynamic forces in turn move, or assist the movement of the control surfaces reducing the amount of mechanical forces needed.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] This arrangement was used in early piston-engined transport aircraft and in early jet transports.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] The Boeing 737 incorporates a system, whereby in the unlikely event of total hydraulic system failure, it automatically and seamlessly reverts to being controlled via servo-tab.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] The complexity and weight of mechanical flight control systems increase considerably with the size and performance of the aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Hydraulically powered control surfaces help to overcome these limitations.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] With hydraulic flight control systems, the aircraft's size and performance are limited by economics rather than a pilot's muscular strength.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] At first, only-partially boosted systems were used in which the pilot could still feel some of the aerodynamic loads on the control surfaces (feedback).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] The pilot's movement of a control causes the mechanical circuit to open the matching servo valve in the hydraulic circuit.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] The hydraulic circuit powers the actuators which then move the control surfaces.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] As the actuator moves, the servo valve is closed by a mechanical feedback linkage - one that stops movement of the control surface at the desired position.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] This arrangement was found in the older-designed jet transports and in some high-performance aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Examples include the Antonov An-225 and the Lockheed SR-71.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] With purely mechanical flight control systems, the aerodynamic forces on the control surfaces are transmitted through the mechanisms and are felt directly by the pilot, allowing tactile feedback of airspeed.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] With hydromechanical flight control systems, the load on the surfaces cannot be felt and there is a risk of overstressing the aircraft through excessive control surface movement.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] To overcome this problem, artificial feel systems can be used.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] For example, for the controls of the RAF's Avro Vulcan jet bomber and the RCAF's Avro Canada CF-105 Arrow supersonic interceptor (both 1950s-era designs), the required force feedback was achieved by a spring device.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] The fulcrum of this device was moved in proportion to the square of the air speed (for the elevators) to give increased resistance at higher speeds.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] For the controls of the American Vought F-8 Crusader and the LTV A-7 Corsair II warplanes, a 'bob-weight' was used in the pitch axis of the control stick, giving force feedback that was proportional to the airplane's normal acceleration.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] A stick shaker is a device that is attached to the control column in some hydraulic aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] It shakes the control column when the aircraft is approaching stall conditions.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Some aircraft such as the McDonnell Douglas DC-10 are equipped with a back-up electrical power supply that can be activated to enable the stick shaker in case of hydraulic failure.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] In most current systems the power is provided to the control actuators by high-pressure hydraulic systems.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] In fly-by-wire systems the valves, which control these systems, are activated by electrical signals.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] In power-by-wire systems, electrical actuators are used in favour of hydraulic pistons.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] The power is carried to the actuators by electrical cables.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] These are lighter than hydraulic pipes, easier to install and maintain, and more reliable.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Elements of the F-35 flight control system are power-by-wire.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] The actuators in such an electro-hydrostatic actuation (EHA) system are self-contained hydraulic devices, small closed-circuit hydraulic systems.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] The overall aim is towards more- or all-electric aircraft and an early example of the approach was the Avro Vulcan.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Serious consideration was given to using the approach on the Airbus A380.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] A fly-by-wire (FBW) system replaces manual flight control of an aircraft with an electronic interface.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] The movements of flight controls are converted to electronic signals transmitted by wires (hence the term *fly-by-wire*), and flight control computers determine how to move the actuators at each control surface to provide the expected response.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Commands from the computers are also input without the pilot's knowledge to stabilize the aircraft and perform other tasks.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Electronics for aircraft flight control systems are part of the field known as avionics.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Fly-by-optics, also known as *fly-by-light*, is a further development using fiber-optic cables.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] These may be used in many unmanned aerial vehicles (UAVs) and 6th generation fighter aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Two promising approaches are flexible wings, and fluidics.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] In flexible wings, also known as "morphing aerofoils", much or all of a wing surface can change shape in flight to deflect air flow much like an ornithopter.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Adaptive compliant wings are a military and commercial effort.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] The X-53 Active Aeroelastic Wing was a US Air Force, NASA, and Boeing effort.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] Notable efforts have also been made by FlexSys, who have conducted flight tests using flexible aerofoils retrofitted to a Gulf stream III aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] In this use, active flow control promises simplicity and lower mass, costs (up to half less), and inertia and response times.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/aircraft-flight-control-system] This was demonstrated in the Demon UAV, which flew for the first time in the UK in September 2010.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] In aviation, **airspeed** is the speed of an aircraft relative to the air it is flying through (which itself is usually moving relative to the ground due to wind).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] In contrast, the ground speed is the speed of an aircraft with respect to the surface of the Earth (whether over land or presumed-stationary water).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] It is difficult to measure the exact airspeed of the aircraft (true airspeed), but other measures of airspeed, such as indicated airspeed and Mach number give useful information about the capabilities and limitations of airplane performance.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] The measurement and indication of airspeed is ordinarily accomplished on board an aircraft by an airspeed indicator (ASI) connected to a pitot-static system.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] The pitot-static system comprises one or more pitot probes (or tubes) facing the on-coming air flow to measure pitot pressure (also called stagnation, total or ram pressure) and one or more static ports to measure the static pressure in the air flow.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] These two pressures are compared by the ASI to give an IAS reading.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] Airspeed indicators are designed to give true airspeed at sea level pressure and standard temperature.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] As the aircraft climbs into less dense air, its true airspeed is greater than the airspeed indicated on the ASI.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] Calibrated airspeed is typically within a few knots of indicated airspeed, while equivalent airspeed decreases slightly from CAS as aircraft altitude increases or at high speeds.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] Airspeed is commonly given in knots (kn).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] Since 2010, the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) recommends using kilometers per hour (km/h) for airspeed (and meters per second for wind speed on runways), but allows using the de facto standard of knots, and has no set date on when to stop.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] Depending on the country of manufacture or which era in aviation history, airspeed indicators on aircraft instrument panels have been configured to read in knots, kilometers per hour, miles per hour.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] In high altitude flight, the Mach number is sometimes used for reporting airspeed.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] Indicated airspeed (IAS) is the airspeed indicator reading (ASIR) uncorrected for instrument, position, and other errors.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] From current EASA definitions: Indicated airspeed means the speed of an aircraft as shown on its pitot static airspeed indicator calibrated to reflect standard atmosphere adiabatic compressible flow at sea level uncorrected for airspeed system errors.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] An airspeed indicator is a differential pressure gauge with the pressure reading expressed in units of speed, rather than pressure.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] The airspeed is derived from the difference between the ram air pressure from the pitot tube, or stagnation pressure, and the static pressure.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] The pitot tube is mounted facing forward; the static pressure is frequently detected at static ports on one or both sides of the aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] Sometimes both pressure sources are combined in a single probe, a pitot-static tube.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] The static pressure measurement is subject to error due to inability to place the static ports at positions where the pressure is true static pressure at all airspeeds and attitudes.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] The correction for this error is the position error correction (PEC) and varies for different aircraft and airspeeds.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] Further errors of 10% or more are common if the airplane is flown in "uncoordinated" flight.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] Indicated airspeed is a better measure of power required and lift available than true airspeed.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] Therefore, IAS is used for controlling the aircraft during taxiing, takeoff, climb, descent, approach or landing.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] Target speeds for best rate of climb, best range, and best endurance are given in terms of indicated speed.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] The airspeed structural limit, beyond which the forces on panels may become too high or wing flutter may occur, is often given in terms of IAS.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] Calibrated airspeed (CAS) is indicated airspeed corrected for instrument errors, position error (due to incorrect pressure at the static port) and installation errors.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] This expression is based on the form of Bernoulli's equation applicable to isentropic compressible flow.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] CAS is the same as true air speed at sea level standard conditions, but becomes smaller relative to true airspeed as we climb into lower pressure and cooler air.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] Nevertheless, it remains a good measure of the forces acting on the airplane, meaning stall speeds can be called out on the airspeed indicator.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] The values for $p_{0}$ and $a_{0}$ are consistent with the ISA i.e. the conditions under which airspeed indicators are calibrated.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] The **true airspeed** (**TAS**; also **KTAS**, for *knots true airspeed*) of an aircraft is the speed of the aircraft relative to the air in which it is flying.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] The true airspeed and heading of an aircraft constitute its velocity relative to the atmosphere.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] The true airspeed is important information for accurate navigation of an aircraft.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] To maintain a desired ground track whilst flying in a moving airmass, the pilot of an aircraft must use knowledge of wind speed, wind direction, and true air speed to determine the required heading.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] TAS is the appropriate speed to use when calculating the range of an airplane.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] It is the speed normally listed on the flight plan, also used in flight planning, before considering the effects of wind.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] Some airspeed indicators include a TAS scale, which is set by entering outside air temperature and pressure altitude.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] Alternatively, TAS can be calculated using an E6B flight calculator or equivalent, given inputs of CAS, outside air temperature (OAT) and pressure altitude.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] Equivalent airspeed (EAS) is defined as the airspeed at sea level in the International Standard Atmosphere at which the (incompressible) dynamic pressure is the same as the dynamic pressure at the true airspeed (TAS) and altitude at which the aircraft is flying.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] EAS is a measure of airspeed that is a function of incompressible dynamic pressure.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] Structural analysis is often in terms of incompressible dynamic pressure, so equivalent airspeed is a useful speed for structural testing.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] The significance of equivalent airspeed is that, at Mach numbers below the onset of wave drag, all of the aerodynamic forces and moments on an aircraft are proportional to the square of the equivalent airspeed.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] Thus, the handling and 'feel' of an aircraft, and the aerodynamic loads upon it, at a given equivalent airspeed, are very nearly constant and equal to those at standard sea level irrespective of the actual flight conditions.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] At standard sea level pressure, CAS and EAS are equal.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] Up to about 200 knots CAS and 10,000 ft (3,000 m) the difference is negligible, but at higher speeds and altitudes CAS diverges from EAS due to compressibility.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] Both the Mach number and the speed of sound can be computed using measurements of impact pressure, static pressure and outside air temperature.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] For aircraft that fly close to, but below the speed of sound (i.e. most civil jets) the compressibility speed limit is given in terms of Mach number.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/airspeed] Beyond this speed, Mach buffet or stall or tuck may occur.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] An **alternator** (or **synchronous generator**) is an electrical generator that converts mechanical energy to electrical energy in the form of alternating current (AC).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] For reasons of cost and simplicity, most alternators use a rotating magnetic field with a stationary armature.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The rotor coil is externally excited by a small direct current (DC), while the AC is generated in the stationary coils.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Occasionally, a linear alternator or a rotating armature with a stationary magnetic field is used.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Although any AC electrical generator might be called an alternator, usually the term refers to small rotating machines driven by automotive and other internal combustion engines.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The term usually applies those types with externally excited rotor coils.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] An alternator that uses a permanent magnet for its magnetic field is called a magneto.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Alternators in power stations driven by steam turbines are called turbo-alternators.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Large 50 or 60 Hz three-phase alternators in power plants generate most of the world's electric power, which is distributed by electric power grids.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Alternating current generating systems were known in simple forms from the discovery of the magnetic induction of electric current in the 1830s.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Rotating generators naturally produced alternating current, but since there was little use for it, it was normally converted into direct current via the addition of a commutator in the generator.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The early machines were developed by pioneers such as Michael Faraday and Hippolyte Pixii.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Faraday developed the "rotating rectangle", whose operation was *heteropolar* – each active conductor passed successively through regions where the magnetic field was in opposite directions.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Lord Kelvin and Sebastian Ferranti also developed early alternators, producing frequencies between 100 and 300 Hz.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The late 1870s saw the introduction of the first large-scale electrical systems with central generation stations to power Arc lamps, used to light whole streets, factory yards, or the interior of large warehouses.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Some, such as Yablochkov arc lamps introduced in 1878, ran better on alternating current, and the development of these early AC generating systems was accompanied by the first use of the word "alternator".
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Supplying the proper amount of voltage from generating stations in these early systems was left up to the engineer's skill in "riding the load".
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] In 1883 the Ganz Works invented the constant voltage generator that could produce a stated output voltage, regardless of the value of the actual load.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The introduction of transformers in the mid-1880s led to the widespread use of alternating current and the use of alternators needed to produce it.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] After 1891, polyphase alternators were introduced to supply currents of multiple differing phases.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Later alternators were designed for various alternating current frequencies between sixteen and about one hundred hertz for use with arc lighting, incandescent lighting, and electric motors.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Specialized radio frequency alternators like the Alexanderson alternator were developed as longwave radio transmitters around World War 1 and used in a few high power wireless telegraphy stations before vacuum tube transmitters replaced them.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] A conductor moving relative to a magnetic field develops an electromotive force (EMF) in it (Faraday's Law).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] This EMF reverses its polarity when it moves under magnetic poles of opposite polarity.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Typically, a rotating magnet, called the rotor, turns within a stationary set of conductors, called the stator, wound in coils on an iron core.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The field cuts across the conductors, generating an induced EMF (electromotive force), as the mechanical input causes the rotor to turn.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The rotating magnetic field induces an AC voltage in the stator windings.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Since the currents in the stator windings vary in step with the position of the rotor, an alternator is a synchronous generator.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The rotor's magnetic field may be produced by permanent magnets or by a field coil electromagnet.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Automotive alternators use a rotor winding, which allows control of the alternator's generated voltage by varying the current in the rotor field winding.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Permanent magnet machines avoid the loss due to magnetizing current in the rotor, but are restricted in size due to the cost of the magnet material.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Since the permanent magnet field is constant, the terminal voltage varies directly with the speed of the generator.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Brushless AC generators are usually larger than those used in automotive applications.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] An automatic voltage control device controls the field current to keep the output voltage constant.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] If the output voltage from the stationary armature coils drops due to an increase in demand, more current is fed into the rotating field coils through the voltage regulator (VR).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] This increases the magnetic field around the field coils, which induces a greater voltage in the armature coils.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Thus, the output voltage is brought back up to its original value.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Alternators used in central power stations also control the field current to regulate reactive power and to help stabilize the power system against the effects of momentary faults.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Often, there are three sets of stator windings, physically offset so that the rotating magnetic field produces a three-phase current, displaced by one-third of a period with respect to each other.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] One cycle of alternating current is produced each time a pair of field poles passes over a point on the stationary winding.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The relation between speed and frequency is $N=120f/P$ , where f is the frequency in Hz (cycles per second).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] P is the number of poles (2, 4, 6, ...), and N is the rotational speed in revolutions per minute (r/min).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Old descriptions of alternating current systems sometimes give the frequency in terms of alternations per minute, counting each half-cycle as one *alternation*; so 12,000 alternations per minute corresponds to 100 Hz.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] An alternator's output frequency depends on the number of poles and the rotational speed.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The speed corresponding to a particular frequency is called the *synchronous speed*.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Alternators may be classified by the method of excitation, number of phases, the type of rotation, cooling method, and their application.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] There are two main ways to produce the magnetic field used in the alternators: by using permanent magnets, which create their persistent magnetic field, or by using field coils.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The alternators that use permanent magnets are specifically called magnetos.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] In other alternators, wound field coils form an electromagnet to produce the rotating magnetic field.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] A device that uses permanent magnets to produce alternating current is called a permanent magnet alternator (PMA).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] A permanent magnet generator (PMG) may produce either alternating current or direct current if it has a commutator.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] This method of excitation consists of a smaller direct-current (DC) generator fixed on the same shaft as the alternator.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The DC generator generates a small amount of electricity, just enough to *excite* the field coils of the connected alternator to generate electricity.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] A variation of this system is a type of alternator that uses direct current from a battery for initial excitation upon start-up, after which the alternator becomes self-excited.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] This method of excitation consists of a smaller alternating-current (AC) generator fixed on the same shaft as the alternator.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The AC stator generates a small amount of field coil excitation current, which is induced in the rotor and rectified to DC by a bridge rectifier built in to the windings where it excites the field coils of the larger connected alternator to generate electricity.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] This system has the advantage of not requiring brushes, which increases service life, although with a slightly lower overall efficiency.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] This method depends on residual magnetism retained in the iron core to generate a weak magnetic field, which would allow a weak voltage to be generated.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] This voltage is used to excite the field coils so the alternator can generate stronger voltage as part of its *build up* process.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] After the initial AC voltage buildup, the field is supplied with rectified voltage from the alternator.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] A brushless alternator is composed of two alternators built end-to-end on one shaft.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Until 1966, alternators used brushes with rotating field.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] With the advancement in semiconductor technology, brushless alternators are possible.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Smaller brushless alternators may look like one unit, but the two parts are readily identifiable in the large versions.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The main alternator is the larger of the two sections, and the smaller one is the exciter.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The exciter has stationary field coils and a rotating armature (power coils).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The main alternator uses the opposite configuration with a rotating field and stationary armature.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] A bridge rectifier, called the rotating rectifier assembly, is mounted on the rotor.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Neither brushes nor slip rings are used, which reduces the number of wearing parts.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The main alternator has a rotating field and a stationary armature (power generation windings).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Varying the amount of current through the stationary exciter field coils varies the 3-phase output from the exciter.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] This output is rectified by a rotating rectifier assembly mounted on the rotor, and the resultant DC supplies the rotating field of the main alternator and hence alternator output.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The result is that a small DC exciter current indirectly controls the output of the main alternator.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Another way to classify alternators is by the number of phases of their output voltage.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The output can be single-phase or polyphase.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Three-phase alternators are the most common, but polyphase alternators can be two-phase, six-phase, or more.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The revolving part of alternators can be the armature or the magnetic field.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The revolving armature type has the armature wound on the rotor, where the winding moves through a stationary magnetic field.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The revolving armature type is not often used.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The revolving field type has a magnetic field on the rotor to rotate through a stationary armature winding.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The stationary armature can be wound for any convenient medium voltage level, up to tens of thousands of volts; manufacture of slip ring connections for more than a few thousand volts is costly and inconvenient.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Many alternators are cooled by ambient air, forced through the enclosure by an attached fan on the shaft that drives the alternator.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] In vehicles such as transit buses, a heavy demand on the electrical system may require a large alternator to be oil-cooled.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] In marine applications water-cooling is also used.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Expensive automobiles may use water-cooled alternators to meet high electrical system demands.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Most power generation stations use synchronous machines as their generators.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The connection of these generators to the utility grid requires synchronization conditions to be met.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Synchronous generators provide several important system services.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Their inherent rotational inertia slows the initial frequency decline after a sudden loss of generation, allowing turbine governors and other frequency-control reserves time to respond and restore balance.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] This role is increasingly significant as the share of non-synchronous generation, such as solar photovoltaics and many modern wind plants, grows in many power systems.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Alternators are used in modern internal combustion engine automobiles to charge the battery and to power the electrical system when its engine is running.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Until the 1960s, automobiles used DC dynamo generators with commutators.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] With the availability of affordable silicon-diode rectifiers, alternators were used instead.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] In later diesel–electric locomotives and diesel–electric multiple units, the prime mover turns an alternator which provides electricity for the traction motors (AC or DC).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The traction alternator usually incorporates integral silicon diode rectifiers to provide the traction motors with up to 1,200 volts DC.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The first diesel electric locomotives, and many of those still in service, use DC generators as, before silicon power electronics, it was easier to control the speed of DC traction motors.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Most of these had two generators: one to generate the excitation current for a larger main generator.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Optionally, the generator also supplies head-end power (HEP) or power for electric train heating.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] The HEP option requires a constant engine speed, typically 900 r/min for a 480 V 60 Hz HEP application, even when the locomotive is not moving.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Marine alternators used in yachts are similar to automotive alternators, with appropriate adaptations to the salt-water environment.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Marine alternators are designed to be explosion proof (ignition protected) so that brush sparking will not ignite explosive gas mixtures in an engine room environment.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Depending on the type of system installed, they may be 12 or 24 volts.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Larger marine diesels may have two or more alternators to cope with the heavy electrical demand of a modern yacht.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] On single alternator circuits, the power may be split between the engine starting battery and the domestic or house battery (or batteries) by use of a split-charge diode (battery isolator) or a voltage-sensitive relay.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Due to the high cost of large house battery banks, Marine alternators generally use external regulators.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Multistep regulators control the field current to maximize the charging effectiveness (time to charge) and battery life.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Multistep regulators can be programmed for different battery types.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Two temperature sensors can be added: one for the battery to adjust the charging voltage and an over-temperature sensor on the actual alternator to protect it from overheating.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] High-frequency alternators of the variable-reluctance type were applied commercially to radio transmission in low-frequency radio bands.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] These were used for transmitting Morse code and, experimentally, for transmitting voice and music.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] In the Alexanderson alternator, both the field winding and armature winding are stationary, and current is induced in the armature by the changing magnetic reluctance of the rotor (which has no windings or current-carrying parts).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/alternator] Such machines were made to produce radio frequency current for radio transmissions, although the efficiency was low.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] In fluid dynamics, **angle of attack** (**AOA**, **α**, or **$\alpha$**) is the angle between a reference line on a body (often the chord line of an airfoil) and the vector representing the relative motion between the body and the fluid through which it is moving.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] Angle of attack is the angle between the body's reference line and the oncoming flow.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] This article focuses on its most common application: the angle of attack of a wing or airfoil moving through air.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] In aerodynamics, angle of attack specifies the angle between the chord line of a fixed wing and the vector representing the relative motion between the aircraft and the atmosphere.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] Since a wing can have twist, a chord line of the whole wing may not be definable, so an alternate reference line is simply defined.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] Often, the chord line of the root of the wing is chosen as the reference line.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] Another choice is to use a horizontal line on the fuselage as the reference line (and also as the longitudinal axis).
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] Some authors do not use an arbitrary chord line but use the zero lift axis where, by definition, zero angle of attack corresponds to zero coefficient of lift.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] Some British authors have used the term angle of incidence instead of angle of attack.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] However, this can lead to confusion with the term *riggers' angle of incidence* meaning the angle between the chord of an airfoil and some fixed datum in the airplane.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] The lift coefficient of a fixed-wing aircraft varies with angle of attack.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] Increasing angle of attack is associated with increasing lift coefficient up to the maximum lift coefficient, after which lift coefficient decreases.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] As the angle of attack of a fixed-wing aircraft increases, separation of the airflow from the upper surface of the wing becomes more pronounced, leading to a reduction in the rate of increase of the lift coefficient.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] The figure shows a typical curve for a cambered straight wing.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] Cambered airfoils are curved such that they generate some lift at small negative angles of attack.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] A symmetrical wing has zero lift at 0 degrees angle of attack.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] The lift curve is also influenced by the wing shape, including its airfoil section and wing planform.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] A swept wing has a lower, flatter curve with a higher critical angle.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] The **critical angle of attack** is the angle of attack which produces the maximum lift coefficient.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] This is also called the "stall angle of attack".
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] Below the critical angle of attack, as the angle of attack decreases, the lift coefficient decreases.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] Conversely, above the critical angle of attack, as the angle of attack increases, the air begins to flow less smoothly over the upper surface of the airfoil and begins to separate from the upper surface.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] On most airfoil shapes, as the angle of attack increases, the upper surface separation point of the flow moves from the trailing edge towards the leading edge.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] At the critical angle of attack, upper surface flow is more separated and the airfoil or wing is producing its maximum lift coefficient.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] As the angle of attack increases further, the upper surface flow becomes more fully separated and the lift coefficient reduces further.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] Above this critical angle of attack, the aircraft is said to be in a stall.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] A fixed-wing aircraft by definition is stalled at or above the critical angle of attack rather than at or below a particular airspeed.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] The airspeed at which the aircraft stalls varies with the weight of the aircraft, the load factor, the center of gravity of the aircraft and other factors.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] However, the aircraft normally stalls at the same critical angle of attack, unless icing conditions prevail.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] The critical or stalling angle of attack is typically around 15° - 18° for many airfoils.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] Some aircraft are equipped with a built-in flight computer that automatically prevents the aircraft from increasing the angle of attack any further when a maximum angle of attack is reached, regardless of pilot input.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] This is called the 'angle of attack limiter' or 'alpha limiter'.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] Modern airliners that have fly-by-wire technology avoid the critical angle of attack by means of software in the computer systems that govern the flight control surfaces.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] In takeoff and landing operations from short runways (STOL), such as Naval Aircraft Carrier operations and STOL backcountry flying, aircraft may be equipped with the angle of attack or Lift Reserve Indicators.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] These indicators measure the angle of attack (AOA) or the Potential of Wing Lift (POWL, or Lift Reserve) directly and help the pilot fly close to the stalling point with greater precision.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] STOL operations require the aircraft to be able to operate close to the critical angle of attack during landings and at the best angle of climb during takeoffs.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] Angle of attack indicators are used by pilots for maximum performance during these maneuvers, since airspeed information is only indirectly related to stall behavior.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] Some military aircraft are able to achieve controlled flight at very high angles of attack, but at the cost of massive induced drag.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] This provides the aircraft with great agility.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] Although the aircraft experiences high angles of attack throughout the maneuver, the aircraft is not capable of either aerodynamic directional control or maintaining level flight until the maneuver ends.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] The Cobra is an example of supermaneuvering as the aircraft's wings are well beyond the critical angle of attack for most of the maneuver.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] Additional aerodynamic surfaces known as "high-lift devices" including leading edge wing root extensions allow fighter aircraft much greater flyable 'true' alpha, up to over 45°, compared to about 20° for aircraft without these devices.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] This can be helpful at high altitudes where even slight maneuvering may require high angles of attack due to the low density of air in the upper atmosphere as well as at low speed at low altitude where the margin between level flight AoA and stall AoA is reduced.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] The high AoA capability of the aircraft provides a buffer for the pilot that makes stalling the airplane (which occurs when critical AoA is exceeded) more difficult.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] However, military aircraft usually do not obtain such high alpha in combat, as it robs the aircraft of speed very quickly due to induced drag, and, in extreme cases, increased frontal area and parasitic drag.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] Not only do such maneuvers slow the aircraft down, but they cause significant structural stress at high speed.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] Modern flight control systems tend to limit a fighter's angle of attack to well below its maximum aerodynamic limit.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] In sailing, the physical principles involved are the same as for aircraft—a sail is an airfoil.
[src:aircraft-engine-controls/angle-of-attack] A sail's **angle of attack** is the angle between the sail's chord line and the direction of the relative wind.
